## **Reflection**

So far, of the ideas that have been thought of 2 have some level of impact and are relatively low effort, the idea of a loneliness website, or a logical fallacy website. The Impact/Effort Matrix shows that there are 2 feasible ideas which are shown to be the logical fallacy website and the loneliness website, however the loneliness website places higher, the SWOT analysis has shown both have their strength and weaknesses, opportunities and threats, however the logical fallacy website already exists, and although slightly outdated and containing self advertisement successfully fills the purpose hence being a major threat to the idea.
 The other idea: the loneliness website, is likely almost banal due to how well known the issue seems to be, however it contains an opportunity that cannot be overlooked, the possibility of extending the idea to those who have too many “friends”, to the point that they aren’t real friends with any of them, hence creating a further sense of loneliness. Due to this opportunity and the pre-existence of the logical fallacy website. I have decided to make my final idea the loneliness website.

## **Requirements Outline**

### Functional Requirements

- The website should be capable of receiving basic inputs from the user  
- The website must have minor customization dependent on the amount of friends the user inputs  
- The website must be capable of remembering the user  
- The website must alter text dependent on inputs.

### Non-Functional Requirements

- Any changes in the website must be seamless  
- Transitions must take place in under a second  
- The website must be easily accessible

## Secondary Research

[Social connections | Australian Bureau of Statistics](https://www.abs.gov.au/statistics/measuring-what-matters/measuring-what-matters-themes-and-indicators/cohesive/social-connections)  
As of 2022, for those aged 15 or over, ⅕ or 20% of people reported feeling lonely often, approaching 2005 levels.  
[Social isolation and loneliness \- Mental health \- AIHW](https://www.aihw.gov.au/mental-health/topic-areas/health-wellbeing/social-isolation-and-loneliness)  
Overall, as of 2023 15% of Australians over 15 were lonely, with those between 15-24 and 35-44 were both higher at 18%

Reflection:  
Overall, it can be seen that loneliness is still a prevalent issue with 20% being an awfully large amount of Australians still suffering from the issue and it is especially interesting to see the minor age-related spikes in loneliness, possibly relating to an overall feeling or to events that happened to the respective generations. Based on this, it can be concluded that there is a reasonable purpose to such a website and it is likely that even a minor impact would still be effective and that there is a sufficient audience for such an idea. 
Furthermore the statistics only represent Australia, loneliness is a global issue and websites have such reach, although it would struggle to reach a non-english audience due to the language barrier, potentially if the website were to be updated in future such language barriers could be accounted for, but such would require a level of skill I certainly lack.

## Peer Evaluations

Going to have ignore this part, as I have no way to contact anyone else in the class.

## Evaluation of Issues

Socially and ethically there are little concerns beyond the account system as no post system has actually been created, there are major ethical concerns surrounding the database and the information it may contain, as if the user is not intelligent they may include sensitive information in their username or password, something far from ideal given that the username is not encrypted. There is also the concern of the right to be forgotten as those who have data on the site have the right to have that information taken down, something that currently isn't possible without further knowledge and the inability to contact. Legally there are also concerns over the procuration of assests (*cough cough downloading images*) and the potential copyright concerns. Although there are some issues most can easily be fixed if the site were to have future updates and hence are negligible in the long-term.

## Project Evaluation

The website is indeed capable of taking user input, editing text based on input and importantly remembering the user being successful in regard to non-functional requirements. Transitions are indeed seamless (if the internet isn't slow), and take place in under a second, the website is also easily accessible not requiring a login, however the choice of colours for the themeing may cause some accessibility issues for those with poor eyesight, there isn't an epilipsy concern due to the static background being blurred (an aesthetic choice), hence it is mostly succesful in regard to non-functional requirements. The project also has a reasonable impact on its target market, for some the simple reminder that they are not alone is enough, that s expected, but it is not a permanent solution, however no website is truly capable of creating a friend for someone from nothing, hence I deem the website successful in its limitations although it could've had a larger impacts with ideas such as others being able to share their own experiences with loneliness. As for the project management, the project was managed terribly, it was assumed (by myself) that I wouldn't be able to understand Flask much and hence a simple project would be required, upon learning javascript this idea was defenstrated as my skill in making websites had exponentially increased and hence the project felt too limited and too simple for my new found skills, leading to boredom and an overall lack of development on the website, hence creating terrible time management, had higher expectations been set by myself, I may have met them with a better website.
